    "In <em>The Lost Meaning of Classical Architecture: Speculations on Ornament from Vitruvius to Venturi</em> (1988) Hersey explored the persistence of the classical orders throughout architectural history.": [],
    "In the 1990s, Hersey became interested in the possibilities of (what would come to be known as) the Digital Humanities.": [],
    "<em>Possible Palladian Villas (Plus a Few Instructively Impossible Ones)</em>, co-authored with computer programmer Richard Freedman in 1992, tested the rigid geometric structures of Palladio\u2019s work and used these rules to generate facades that are ostensibly indistinguishable from those of the architect.": [],
    "In the final years of his career \u2014 he retired from Yale in 1998 \u2014 Hersey produced two books that linked Darwinian ideas to art history.": [],
    "<em>The Evolution of Allure: Sexual Selection from the Medici Venus to the Incredible Hulk</em> (1996) argued that art has had a significant impact on human evolution.": [],
    "<em>The Monumental Impulse: Architecture's Biological Roots</em> (1999), builds on the thesis of his prior book by exploring the relationship between microscopic organisms and architecture.": [],
